{"key":"processedPost-13952989","value":{"id":13952989,"first":13945934,"last":13952989,"when":1297564688,"utime":"02/13/11 04:38 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>DJYoshaBYD said:</b><br /><br />i know.. hahahaha.. this is crazy.. but doesnt it seem more like that evaporation is secondary to removing the CO2?<br /><br />RR - Can you explain this? im looking everywhere online, and the only place i see this info is on this forum, while everywhere else refers to removal of CO2, which by common sense, causes a secondary effect of evaporation?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />It's not an either/or situation.&nbsp; Evaporation of moisture from the substrate is the main pinning trigger.&nbsp; Now, if you dry out the substrate but still have a high CO2 level, pinning will be poor.&nbsp; By the same token, if you lower the CO2 level, but saturate the substrate, pinning will also be poor.<br /><br />I've often phrased it as \"fresh air exchange is the number one pinning trigger\", and I've often said the same thing as \"loss of moisture from a substrate is the number one pinning trigger\".&nbsp; Both are true, but loss of moisture is perhaps slightly more important.&nbsp; I use a fluctuating humidity and a CO2 level of less than 1000 ppm, maintained by the amount of air my blower is exchanging.<br />RR","title":"Re: 4 cakes 1 mushroom....WTF"}}